    "summary": "The Palestine Liberation Organization was founded in May 1964 at an Arab League summit in Cairo, initially under Egyptian patronage, with the stated goal of liberating Palestine through armed struggle. Yasser Arafat's Fatah movement gradually took control of the PLO following the defeat of Arab armies in the [[event:2686|Six-Day War]] of 1967, and Arafat became PLO chairman in 1969. Under his leadership, the PLO established itself as an autonomous political and military force operating from bases in Jordan, Lebanon, and Tunisia.\n\nThe PLO pioneered modern political terrorism as a tool of national liberation, including aircraft hijackings, the 1972 Munich Olympics massacre carried out by the Black September faction, and numerous attacks in Israel and against Jewish targets abroad. In 1974, the Arab League recognized the PLO as the sole legitimate representative of the Palestinian people, and Arafat addressed the UN General Assembly. The organization's character evolved from purely military to diplomatic after the PLO recognized Israel's right to exist in 1988 and renounced terrorism. This shift enabled the [[event:2720|Oslo Accords]] of 1993, which established the Palestinian Authority as a governing body in parts of the West Bank and Gaza.",
